The latest report from the United Nations World Tourism Organisation’ (UNWO) World Tourism Barometre has shown that Africa continent generated $38 billion from tourism in 2018, recording 67 million tourists within the same period.  According to the report, international tourism for Europe and Africa grew at equal levels of four per cent for the first quarter of 2019. This is in accord to the UNWTO’s forecast of three to four per cent growth for this year.  Details of the report shows that North Africa’s recovery led to 11 per cent of growth.  “International tourism continues to perform strongly worldwide fueled by a positive economy, increased air capacity and visa facilitation,” said UNWTO Secretary General, Zurab Pololikashvili. The UNWTO barometer data also shows tourism receipts for Europe reached $571 billion for 713 million arrivals. It indicated also that tourism has started to pick up after slowing down at the end of 2018 and believes performance for the first three months was a positive sign.